article.description:
Chris Whitney scored 20 points, including
five in the final 12.8 seconds, and the Washington Wizards beat the
Golden State Warriors 99-96 Monday night.
article.headline: Whitney allows Wizards to edge Warriors
article.linkText: Wizards win rare game without Jordan
article.story:
OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) --It was just how the Washington Wizards drew it up. Playing their fourth game of a seven-game road trip, all without Michael Jordan, the Wizards seemed destined for their seventh loss in eight games after the Golden State Warriors took control in the fourth quarter behind the rookie backcourt of Gilbert Arenas and Jason Richardson, who combined for 46 points. But each missed key free throws down the stretch and Chris Whitney scored five points in the final 12.8 seconds, including a key 3-pointer, to lift Washington to a 99-96 victory, only its fourth in 12 starts since Jordan went down with a knee injury. Whitney led the charge with 20 points, followed by Richard Hamilton with 17, Tyron Nesby 15, Popeye Jones 12 and Courtney Alexander 10. Washington (31-36) is 2.5 games back of Charlotte for the final playoff spot in the East with 15 games remaining. Jordan is questionable for Wednesday's game at Denver. "This is the kind of game we needed to win," said Jones, who led a 45-20 edge off the bench. "Everybody has had us buried a long time ago. But it's a credit to the coaches and players that we've remained so tough." "I told our guys that they've worked too hard this season to lose this game. They believed we were going to win," said Washington coach Doug Collins. With his team down 96-94 with 22 seconds left, Collins called timeout. The Wizards set up a screen for Hamilton, but Christian Laettner picked off Arenas leaving Whitney wide open on the left flank. Tyronn Lue fed Whitney, who buried it with 12.8 seconds left giving Washington its first lead of the fourth quarter. "Coach drew it up perfectly," Whitney said. "I just had to shoot it. I felt confident when I got it and when it left my hands I had a good feeling it was going to drop." After Arenas was called for a charging into Jones with 6.7 seconds left, Whitney hit two free throws with 5.9 ticks left. A desperation 3-pointer by Arenas fell well short, giving the Wizards just their fourth win in 12 tries without Jordan. "Coach told us that if we didn't win these next two games it didn't look like we were going to the playoffs," Whitney said. "We had to take care of business." Arenas scored a career-high 25 to lead the Warriors, who started three rookies for the first time since 1995. Richardson added 21 points, Antawn Jamison 16 and Chris Mills 12. Golden State (17-48) has lost nine of 12. "I thought we played a good game and lost," Golden State coach Brian Winters said. The Wizards' bench outscored the Warriors 35-8 in the first half while taking a 56-54 lead. Nesby, who finished with 10 rebounds, and Kwame Brown each connected on 4 of 5 shots as Washington hit 52 percent of its shots while the Warriors made 51 percent, including 4-for-4 by Arenas. He and Richardson had 11 points and Jamison 12. Arenas heated up in the third quarter, scoring 11 points in the first 5:20. He finally missed his first shot with 1:31 left in the third, a 3-point try, after making seven straight. "I didn't realize Gilbert was that fast or that good," Whitney said. Neither team could pull away as there were four ties and six lead changes in the third quarter alone. A four-point play by Mills helped give Golden State a 79-78 lead heading into the fourth. Finally, the Warriors put together a 6-0 run to start the fourth quarter, capped by a reverse windmill dunk by Richardson to put Golden State up 85-78. It was its largest lead since the first quarter and the Warriors held it until Whitney's late 3-pointer. Game notes
The Wizards are 27-26 with Jordan in the lineup and 4-10 without him. He was expected to return sometime late in the current road trip - the Wizards have three more road games starting Wednesday in Denver -- but it's doubtful he'll return then. He's still on the injured list... Golden State's Larry Hughes missed his 20th straight 3-pointer in the first half and is now 2 for his last 40.With 30 wins coming in, the Wizards already have 11 more than all of last season... All 14 players on Golden State's roster participated in the NCAA Tournament.
